The temperature-dependent MCDs showed UV absorbance at 292nm. The MCDs prepared at 100°C (Fig. S2, line i) were a pale yellow color, whereas a brown solution was obtained when they were prepared at 140°C (Fig. S2, line ii). The color significantly darkened when increasing the reaction temperature to 170°C. Therefore, it is expected that the MCDs prepared at higher temperatures may show much stronger fluorescent signals than those prepared at lower temperatures due to the complete nucleation of MCDs formation. The TEM images (Fig. 5
                        ) strongly suggest the stepwise nucleation of biomolecules with temperatures (100, 140 and 170°C). The results are coincided with XRD pattern. The fluorescence efficiency of the MCDs was estimated by the calculation of the QY of the MCDs. MCDs prepared at 170°C showed 25% QY, which was decreased to 16 and 3% when decreasing the reaction temperature to 140 and 100°C, respectively. Therefore, MCDs prepared at 170°C were used for further analysis of their optical properties. The UV–vis absorption and PL excitation dependent emission spectra of the MCDs (170°C) in aqueous solution are presented in (Fig. 6
                        ). The characteristic strong absorption peak of the MCDs appeared at 292nm, which can be attributed to the π–π* transition of the CC bonds of the sp2 hybridized aromatic domains and the n–π* transition of CO, COOH, and NH2 bonds (line i). The absorbance peak clearly indicates that the MCDs featured enormous numbers of polar functional groups on their surface [50]. When they were irradiated with UV light (360nm), strong blue fluorescence (456nm) was emitted from the solution (Fig. 6A, line ii and iii); the right inset image shows the color of the MCD solution without and with UV irradiation. The MCD solution exhibited excitation dependent emission (Fig. 6B) that was highly consistent with previous observations [51]. The PL excitation-dependent emission spectrum shows that the PL emission peak exhibited a redshift transition from 430 to 570nm when the excitation wavelength was shifted from 320 to 500nm. The maximum emission intensity was observed when the MCD solution was excited with 360nm light, which may be due to the synergistic effects of the carbogenic core, multiphoton active process, and very fine crystal defects in the MCDs [52]. The unique fluorescent properties with high QY suggest that MCDs have great potential for applications of sensing and bio-engineering.
